"Token endpoint attached to the Spring Boot app" — no, this is the mixup. The gateway doesn't have or call a token endpoint. The token endpoint belongs to Keycloak (something like http://keycloak/realms/myrealm/protocol/openid-connect/token), and it's used by whoever acquires a token — that could be a curl command you run manually for testing, or a real frontend doing PKCE. The gateway itself never hits that endpoint. The gateway only needs to know where to fetch Keycloak's public keys to verify a token's signature — that's a different endpoint (JWKS), and Spring fetches it automatically once you tell it the realm's issuer URL.

"There should be a client added to Keycloak" — yes, but be clear on why: that client isn't "attached to" or "used by" the gateway. It exists purely so that you (for testing) or a real frontend (for production) have something to request a token from. The gateway doesn't reference this client, doesn't authenticate as it, doesn't know it exists. It's a completely separate concern from the gateway's config.

The corrected, precise flow
Keycloak has a realm + a client (this client is for whoever gets tokens — you, testing manually, or a real frontend later)
You (for now) call Keycloak's token endpoint directly with username/password → get back a JWT
You send a request to the gateway with that JWT in the Authorization: Bearer <token> header
Gateway (configured with just the realm's issuer URL, nothing about "the client") automatically fetches Keycloak's public keys, verifies the token's signature and expiry
If valid → gateway's security filter lets the request through to your rate limiter/circuit breaker/downstream service. If invalid → gateway rejects with 401, before any of your other filters even run.
The one-sentence fix to your understanding
The client in Keycloak is for acquiring tokens (used by whoever logs in). The gateway only needs the realm's issuer URL to verify tokens — it has no direct relationship with any specific client. Those are two separate, unconnected setups happening in the same Keycloak instance.

