Let's nail down ShopNetic's actual flow first, since you're recalling it correctly but let's make it precise, then map the gateway onto the same pattern — because it genuinely is the same pattern, just gateway replaces "backend."

ShopNetic's actual flow (Authorization Code + PKCE)
User opens Angular frontend, clicks login
Frontend redirects the browser to Keycloak's login page (not an API call — an actual redirect, user sees Keycloak's UI)
User enters username/password directly into Keycloak's page, not your frontend's
Keycloak redirects back to your frontend with an authorization code
Frontend exchanges that code (+ PKCE verifier) for a JWT — this exchange call goes to Keycloak's token endpoint
Frontend now holds a JWT, attaches it as Authorization: Bearer <token> on every API call to ShopNetic backend
ShopNetic backend receives the request, validates the JWT (checks signature against Keycloak's public key, checks expiry, checks claims) — this is Spring Security's OAuth2 Resource Server doing the work, you didn't hand-write JWT parsing
If valid, backend processes the request; if invalid, backend returns 401
So ShopNetic backend was already acting as a Resource Server. You just didn't necessarily think of it in those terms — it received tokens issued elsewhere (Keycloak) and verified them, never issued anything itself.

Gateway's flow — identical shape, gateway replaces ShopNetic backend
1-6 are exactly the same, unchanged. Frontend still does PKCE against Keycloak, still gets a JWT, still attaches it to requests.

The only change: in step 6, instead of the frontend calling ShopNetic directly, it now calls your gateway. The gateway does what ShopNetic backend used to do (validate the token), then forwards the request onward to ShopNetic (or whatever service).

OLD:  Frontend → (JWT) → ShopNetic backend [validates + processes]

NEW:  Frontend → (JWT) → Gateway [validates only] → ShopNetic backend [just processes, trusts gateway]
This is literally moving the validation step one hop earlier in the chain. Nothing about how the frontend gets tokens changes at all.

Now — JwtAuthenticationConverter, what it actually is
You're right that you'll write this, but let's be precise about what it does versus what Spring already does for you.

Spring already handles, automatically, no code from you:

Fetching Keycloak's public keys (JWKS)
Verifying the token's signature is legitimate (not tampered with)
Checking the token hasn't expired
What JwtAuthenticationConverter does, which you do write: Keycloak's JWT contains claims — things like sub (user ID), realm_access.roles (a list like ["ADMIN", "CUSTOMER"]), preferred_username, etc. Spring, out of the box, doesn't know which claim in that JSON blob represents "this user's roles" — Keycloak's structure is slightly nonstandard compared to Spring Security's default expectations. JwtAuthenticationConverter is the piece of code that says: "look inside realm_access.roles, pull that list out, and turn it into Spring Security authorities/roles that the rest of the security config can use for things like @PreAuthorize or route-based access rules."

So concretely, its job: extract the token's already-verified claims and reshape them into a form Spring Security's authorization logic understands — not "verify the token" (that already happened before this converter even runs), but "interpret what's inside it."

Where this fits in the sequence, precisely
Request arrives at gateway with JWT
Spring Security's resource server filter verifies signature + expiry (automatic, no code)
Then JwtAuthenticationConverter runs — pulls roles/claims out of the now-verified token
Your security config uses those extracted roles to decide: does this user have permission for this route?
If everything passes, gateway forwards to downstream, optionally attaching specific claims as headers so ShopNetic doesn't need to re-parse the JWT itself
