That line describes step 5 of the PKCE flow — the final handoff where the frontend actually gets its hands on a usable token. Let's unpack it piece by piece.

What happened just before this line
Steps 1-4 (redirect to Keycloak, user logs in, Keycloak redirects back) leave the frontend holding just an authorization code — a short-lived, single-use string, NOT a JWT yet. Think of it like a claim ticket: proof that login succeeded, but not the actual token you need.

What "exchanges that code (+ PKCE verifier) for a JWT" means
The frontend now makes a direct HTTP call (not a browser redirect this time — an actual backend-style API call, done by the frontend's own code) to Keycloak's token endpoint. Something like:

POST http://keycloak/realms/myrealm/protocol/openid-connect/token
Body:
  grant_type=authorization_code
  code=<the authorization code from step 4>
  code_verifier=<the PKCE secret the frontend generated earlier>
  client_id=<your client id>
Keycloak checks: does this code match what I issued? Does this code_verifier match the code_challenge the frontend sent at the very start of the flow (before redirecting to login)? If both check out, Keycloak trusts that the same app that started the login flow is the one finishing it — that's literally what PKCE protects against (a stolen authorization code being used by an attacker who isn't the original app).

What "this exchange call goes to Keycloak's token endpoint" means
Just naming which Keycloak URL handles this — the "token endpoint," a specific API path Keycloak exposes (/protocol/openid-connect/token) whose whole job is: "give me a code, I'll give you back a token." This is different from the login page URL (which is for the browser redirect) — the token endpoint is a machine-to-machine API call, not something a human sees in a browser.

The result
Keycloak's response to this call is the actual JWT — the frontend now has a real, usable access token for the first time in the whole flow. Everything before this point (steps 1-4) was just proving "yes, this user really did log in" — this step is where that proof gets converted into the token that'll actually be sent to your APIs.

