This is Keycloak's client configuration screen — settings that control how a client is allowed to get tokens. Let's go through each one.

Client authentication — currently OFF
This toggle decides whether this client needs to prove its own identity (a client secret) when talking to Keycloak, in addition to whatever the user does.

OFF = "public client" — no secret required. This is correct for browser-based apps (like your Angular frontend) because a secret embedded in frontend JavaScript isn't actually secret — anyone can view-source and see it. PKCE exists specifically to secure public clients without needing a secret.
ON = "confidential client" — requires a client secret, used for server-side apps (a backend service calling Keycloak directly, where the secret can stay hidden on the server).
For your gateway, since it's not doing any Keycloak flow at all (remember — it's just a resource server, verifying tokens), this setting barely matters for the gateway itself. It matters for whichever client the frontend uses to log in.

Authorization — currently OFF
This is Keycloak's fine-grained authorization services (resource-based permissions, policies, scopes — a whole separate authorization engine). Overkill for what you're doing; leave off. Not related to basic JWT validation at all.

Authentication flow — this is the important section
These checkboxes control which OAuth2/OIDC flows this client is allowed to use to get tokens:

Standard flow ✓ (checked) — this is Authorization Code flow, the one ShopNetic uses, the one requiring a browser redirect to Keycloak's login page. Correct for a real frontend client.
Direct access grants (unchecked) — this is Resource Owner Password Credentials, the "send username+password straight to the token endpoint, skip the browser" flow I mentioned earlier for quick testing. If you want to generate test tokens via curl without going through a browser login, you'd need to check this box on whatever client you're using for testing.
Implicit flow — an older, now-discouraged flow that returned tokens directly in the redirect URL. Leave unchecked; nobody should use this anymore.
Service account roles — for machine-to-machine auth where the client itself (not a human user) gets a token representing itself. Not relevant to your current flow.
Standard Token Exchange — lets one token be exchanged for another (e.g., a gateway swapping a user's token for a service-specific token). Advanced, not needed yet.
OAuth 2.0 Device Authorization Grant — for devices without browsers (smart TVs, CLI tools) where you log in on a separate device. Not relevant here.
OIDC CIBA Grant — decoupled auth, login happens on a separate device that isn't the one making the request (e.g., a banking app push notification approval). Not relevant here.